\section{Related Work}

\paragraph{Training-based concept erasure.}
A prominent line of work modifies diffusion model parameters to permanently remove unsafe concepts. ESD~\citep{gandikota2023erasing} fine-tunes cross-attention layers to minimize the probability of generating target concepts; SDD~\citep{kim2023towards} uses self-distillation to steer weights toward a safer distribution; UCE~\citep{gandikota2024unified} introduces closed-form weight updates that remove the iterative training loop; and RECE~\citep{gong2024reliable} strengthens reliability through eraser ensembles. Alternative fine-tuning strategies include Concept Ablation~\citep{kumari2023ablating} and Forget-Me-Not~\citep{zhang2024forget}. These methods achieve strong suppression for specific concepts but share fundamental limitations: each concept requires separate training, parameter modification risks catastrophic forgetting, and the altered model remains constrained even on benign prompts.

\paragraph{Training-free inference-time guidance.}
An alternative paradigm preserves model parameters and intervenes only during inference. SLD~\citep{schramowski2023safe} manipulates classifier-free guidance (CFG) to steer denoising trajectories away from harmful concepts at four preset strengths. SEGA~\citep{brack2023sega} extends this with semantic guidance directions. SAFREE~\citep{yoon2024safree} operates jointly in text and latent spaces, projecting harmful tokens orthogonal to a toxic subspace, and is the current state-of-the-art training-free baseline with native multi-concept support. Safe Denoiser~\citep{kim2025training} uses a negation-set formulation to derive a provably safer sampling trajectory. However, all of these methods apply suppression \emph{globally} across the latent, inevitably causing semantic drift and quality degradation for the benign portion of a prompt. A closely related workshop paper, ASCG~\citep{kil2026ascg}, introduced spatial selectivity via Grad-CAM localization but relied on an auxiliary classifier and lacked multi-concept support. \ours{} departs from this line by replacing classifier-based detection with exemplar-pack-based CLIP embeddings, introducing a family-indexed dual-probe mechanism with pixel-wise winner-take-all, and admitting two complementary How modes (anchor inpainting, hybrid guidance) within the same framework.

\paragraph{Adversarial benchmarks and metaphorical jailbreaks.}
Evaluating safety methods under adversarial pressure motivates several benchmarks. Ring-A-Bell~\citep{tsai2023ring}, UnlearnDiff~\citep{zhang2024generate}, and MMA-Diffusion~\citep{yang2024mma} craft adversarial prompts targeting nudity with progressively more implicit phrasing. MJA (Metaphor-based Jailbreaking Attack)~\citep{zhang2026reason2attack} uses LLM reasoning to produce prompts that evade keyword filters entirely (\eg, ``showing raw strength'' for violence), and currently exposes the largest gap between training-free defenses and ground truth. Our evaluation uses all four datasets plus I2P~\citep{schramowski2023safe} subsets for multi-concept coverage, and introduces per-concept probe-dominance analysis that connects benchmark difficulty to detection modality (Appendix~\ref{app:probe_dominance}).

\paragraph{Safety evaluators for T2I.}
Automated safety classifiers such as NudeNet~\citep{notai_nudenet_2019} and the Q16 detector~\citep{schramowski2022can} provide scalable judgments but lack semantic context. Recent VLM-based evaluators deliver more nuanced free-form analyses, and MJ-Bench~\citep{chen2024mj} provides a standardized protocol for evaluating such judges on safety preference tasks. We adopt Qwen3-VL-8B~\citep{bai2025qwen3} as our primary evaluator, validate it against MJ-Bench, and cross-check against an independent LLaVA~\citep{liu2023visual} judge; detailed validator analysis is in Appendix~\ref{app:evaluator}.
